Chat

Class CheckersData

  • java.lang.Object
    • Chat.CheckersData

  • public class CheckersData
extends java.lang.Object
    An object of this class holds data about a game of checkers. It knows what kind of piece is on each square of the checkerboard. Note that RED moves "up" the board (i.e. row number decreases) while BLACK moves "down" the board (i.e. row number increases). Methods are provided to return lists of available legal moves.
    Version:
    May 25, 2015
    Author:
    Jessica, NanXi, Prachi, Period: 2, Assignment: CHECKERS, Sources: David Eck

    • Method Detail

      • setUpGame

        public void setUpGame()
        Set up the board with checkers in position for the beginning of a game. Note that checkers can only be found in squares that satisfy row % 2 == col % 2. At the start of the game, all such squares in the first three rows contain black squares and all such squares in the last three rows contain red squares.

      • makeMove

        public void makeMove(int fromRow,
            int fromCol,
            int toRow,
            int toCol,
            CheckersMove m)
        Make the move from (fromRow,fromCol) to (toRow,toCol). It is assumed that this move is legal. If the move is a jump, the jumped piece is removed from the board. If a piece moves to the last row on the opponent's side of the board, the piece becomes a king.
        Parameters:
        fromRow - the row from which the piece is moved
        fromCol - the col from which the piece is moved
        toRow - the row to which the piece is moved
        toCol - the col to which the piece is moved
        m - the move itself

      • getLegalMoves

        public CheckersMove[] getLegalMoves(int player)
        Return an array containing all the legal CheckersMoves for the specified player on the current board. If the player has no legal moves, null is returned. The value of player should be one of the constants RED or BLACK; if not, null is returned. If the returned value is non-null, it consists entirely of jump moves or entirely of regular moves, since if the player can jump, only jumps are legal moves.
        Parameters:
        player - is the type of player (red, red king, black, black king)
        Returns:
        an array of legal moves

      • getLegalJumpsFrom

        public CheckersMove[] getLegalJumpsFrom(int player,
                               int row,
                               int col)
        Return a list of the legal jumps that the specified player can make starting from the specified row and column. If no such jumps are possible, null is returned. The logic is similar to the logic of the getLegalMoves() method.
        Parameters:
        player - is the type of player (red, red king, black, black king)
        row - is the row the piece jumps from
        col - is the col the piece jumps from
        Returns:
        an array of all the possible jump moves

      • canJump

        public boolean canJump(int player,
              int r1,
              int c1,
              int r2,
              int c2,
              int r3,
              int c3)
        This is called by the two previous methods to check whether the player can legally jump from (r1,c1) to (r3,c3). It is assumed that the player has a piece at (r1,c1), that (r3,c3) is a position that is 2 rows and 2 columns distant from (r1,c1) and that (r2,c2) is the square between (r1,c1) and (r3,c3).
        Parameters:
        player - is the type of player (red, red king, black, black king)
        r1 - the row position the piece can jump from
        c1 - the col position the piece can jump from
        r2 - the row position the piece can jump over
        c2 - the col position the piece can jump over
        r3 - the row position the piece can jump to
        c3 - the col position the piece can jump to
        Returns:
        whether the piece can make a legal jump or not

      • canMove

        public boolean canMove(int player,
              int r1,
              int c1,
              int r2,
              int c2)
        This is called by the getLegalMoves() method to determine whether the player can legally move from (r1,c1) to (r2,c2). It is assumed that (r1,r2) contains one of the player's pieces and that (r2,c2) is a neighboring square.
        Parameters:
        player - is the type of player (red, red king, black, black king)
        r1 - the row position the piece can move from
        c1 - the col position the piece can move from
        r2 - the row position the piece can move to
        c2 - the col position the piece can move to
        Returns:
        whether the piece can make a legal move or not
